Eliding Async and Await  省略 Async 和 Await

8 years ago (Dec 1, 2016) • 52 Comments
8 年前 （Dec 1， 2016） • 52 評論

Once one has learned the basics of async and await and has gotten fairly comfortable with it, a common design question often comes up: If I can remove async and await, should I? There are a number of situations where you can elide the async/await keywords and just return the task directly.
一旦你學會了 async 和 await 的基礎知識，並且相當熟悉它，一個常見的設計問題經常會出現：如果我能去掉 async 和 await，我應該去掉嗎？在許多情況下，你可以省略 async/await 關鍵字，直接返回任務。

This is a surprisingly nuanced question, and in fact I now hold to a different answer than the position I originally took on this issue.
這是一個令人驚訝的微妙問題，事實上，我現在的答案與我最初在這個問題上採取的立場不同。

First, let’s check out the argument in favor of eliding the keywords.
首先，讓我們看看贊成省略關鍵字的論點。

Efficiency  效率

It’s more efficient to elide async and await. By not including these keywords, the compiler can skip generating the async state machine. This means that there are fewer compiler-generated types in your assembly, less pressure on the garbage collector, and fewer CPU instructions to execute.
省略 async 和 await 效率更高。通過不包含這些關鍵字，編譯器可以跳過生成異步狀態機。這意味著程式集中編譯器生成的類型更少，垃圾回收器的壓力更小，要執行的 CPU 指令也更少。

However, it’s important to point out that each of these gains are absolutely minimal. There’s one fewer type, a handful of small objects saved from GC, and only a few CPU instructions skipped. The vast majority of the time, async is dealing with I/O, which completely dwarfs any performance gains. In almost every scenario, eliding async and await doesn’t make any difference to the running time of your application.
但是，重要的是要指出，這些收益中的每一個都是絕對微乎其微的。少了一個類型，從 GC 保存的少量小對象，並且只跳過了幾條CPU指令。絕大多數情況下，async 處理的是 I/O，這完全使任何性能提升相形見絀。在幾乎所有情況下，省略 async 和 await 都不會對應用程式的運行時間產生任何影響。

For a thorough overview of the efficiency benefits of eliding async and await, see Stephen Toub’s classic video The Zen of Async or his MSDN article on the subject.
有關省略 async 和 await 的效率優勢的全面概述，請參閱 Stephen Toub 的經典視頻 The Zen of Async 或他關於該主題的 MSDN 文章。

When I started writing about async, I would always recommend eliding async and await, but I’ve modified that stand in recent years. There are just too many pitfalls to recommend eliding as a default decision. These days I recommend keeping the async and await keywords around except for a few scenarios, because of the drawbacks described in the rest of this blog post.
當我開始寫 async 時，我總是建議省略 async 和 await，但近年來我修改了這個立場。有太多的陷阱，建議將省略作為默認決定。如今，我建議保留 async 和 await 關鍵字，除了少數情況，因為本篇博文的其餘部分描述了這些缺點。

Pitfalls  陷阱

By eliding async and await, you can avoid the compiler modifications to your method. Unfortunately, this also means that all the compiler modifications to your method must now be done by hand if you desire the same semantics.
通過省略 async 和 await，可以避免編譯器對方法的修改。不幸的是，這也意味著，如果您希望相同的語義，現在必須手動完成對方法的所有編譯器修改。

Using  用

One of the most common mistakes in eliding async and await is that developers forget that there is code at the end of their method that needs to run at the appropriate time. In particular, when using a using statement:
省略 async 和 await 最常見的錯誤之一是開發人員忘記了他們的方法末尾有代碼需要在適當的時間運行。特別是，當使用using語句時：

In this example, eliding the keywords will abort the download.
在此範例中，省略關鍵字將中止下載。

It’s easier to understand if you walk through how the code progresses (if you need a review, my intro to async and await post is still perfectly relevant today). For simplicity, I’ll assume that HttpClient.GetStringAsync never completes synchronously.
如果您瞭解代碼的進展情況，則更容易理解（如果您需要回顧一下，我的 async 和 await 簡介帖子在今天仍然非常相關）。為簡單起見，我假設 HttpClient.GetStringAsync 永遠不會同步完成。

With GetWithKeywordsAsync, the code does this:
使用 GetWithKeywordsAsync，代碼將執行以下作：

  1. Create the HttpClient object.
    創建 HttpClient 物件。
  2. Invoke GetStringAsync, which returns an incomplete task.
    調用 GetStringAsync，這將返回一個未完成的任務。
  3. Pauses the method until the task returned from GetStringAsync completes, returning an incomplete task.
    暫停該方法，直到從 GetStringAsync 返回的任務完成，並返回未完成的任務。
  4. When the task returned from GetStringAsync completes, it resumes executing the method.
    當從 GetStringAsync 傳回的任務完成時，它會繼續執行該方法。
  5. Disposes the HttpClient object.
    釋放 HttpClient 物件。
  6. Completes the task previously returned from GetWithKeywordsAsync.
    完成以前從 GetWithKeywordsAsync 返回的任務。

With GetElidingKeywordsAsync, the code does this:
使用 GetElidingKeywordsAsync，代碼將執行以下作：

  1. Create the HttpClient object.
    創建 HttpClient 物件。
  2. Invoke GetStringAsync, which returns an incomplete task.
    調用 GetStringAsync，這將返回一個未完成的任務。
  3. Disposes the HttpClient object.
    釋放 HttpClient 物件。
  4. Returns the task that was returned from GetStringAsync.
    返回從 GetStringAsync 返回的任務。

Clearly, the HttpClient is disposed before the GET task completes, and this causes that request to be cancelled. The appropriate fix is to (asynchronously) wait until the GET operation is complete, and only then dispose the HttpClient, which is exactly what happens if you use async and await.
顯然，HttpClient 在 GET 任務完成之前被釋放，這會導致該請求被取消。適當的解決方法是（異步）等待 GET作完成，然後才釋放 HttpClient，這正是使用 async 和 await 時發生的情況。

Exceptions  異常

Another easily-overlooked pitfall is that of exceptions. The state machine for async methods will capture exceptions from your code and place them on the returned task. Without the async keyword, the exception is raised directly rather than going on the task:
另一個容易被忽視的陷阱是異常。異步方法的狀態機將從你的代碼中捕獲異常，並將它們放在返回的任務上。如果沒有 async 關鍵字，則直接引發異常，而不是繼續執行任務：

These methods work exactly the same as long as the calling method does something like this:
只要調用方法執行如下作，這些方法的工作方式就完全相同：

However, if the method call is separated from the await, then the semantics are different:
但是，如果 method 調用與 await 分開，則語義不同：

The invocation of the method can be separated from the await in a variety of cases. For example, the calling method may have other work to do concurrently with the asynchronous work done by our method. This is most common in code that uses Task.WhenAll.
在多種情況下，該方法的調用可以與 await 分開。例如，調用方法可能有其他工作要與我們的方法完成的異步工作同時進行。這在使用Task.WhenAll的代碼中最為常見。

The expected asynchronous semantics are that exceptions are placed on the returned task. Since the returned task represents the execution of the method, if that execution of that method is terminated by an exception, then the natural representation of that scenario is a faulted task.
預期的異步語義是將異常放置在返回的任務上。由於返回的任務表示方法的執行，因此，如果該方法的執行由異常終止，則該場景的自然表示為出錯的任務。

So, eliding the keywords in this case causes different (and unexpected) exception behavior.
因此，在這種情況下省略關鍵字會導致不同的 （和意外的） 異常行為。

AsyncLocal  異步本地

This pitfall is a bit harder to reason about.
這個陷阱有點難以推理。

AsyncLocal<T> (and the lower-level LogicalCallContext) allow asynchronous code to use a kind of async-compatible almost-equivalent of thread local storage. The way that this actually works is that as part of the async compiler transformation, the compiler-generated code will notify the logical call context that it needs to establish a copy-on-write scope.
AsyncLocal<T>（和較低級別的LogicalCallContext）允許異步代碼使用一種異步相容的、幾乎等同於線程本地存儲的存儲。實際的工作方式是，作為異步編譯器轉換的一部分，編譯器生成的代碼將通知邏輯調用上下文它需要建立寫入時複製範圍。

This provides a way for contextual information to flow “down” asynchronous calls. Note that the value does not flow “up”.
這為上下文資訊提供了一種“向下”異步調用的方法。請注意，該值不會 「向上」 流動。

In the example above, the context value is set in the “child” Async method, but when Async completes and the control flow moves back to MainAsync, the code executes in the “parent” context. So the “parent” value flows to the “child”, but the “child” value does not flow to the “parent”.
在上面的示例中，上下文值在“子”Async 方法中設置，但當 Async 完成並且控制流移回 MainAsync 時，代碼將在“父”上下文中執行。因此，“parent” 值流向 “child”，但 “child” 值不會流向 “parent”。

The pitfall is that synchronous methods do not notify the logical call context that anything is different. For normal (non-task-returning) synchronous methods, this works out fine; from the logical call context’s perspective, all synchronous invocations are “collapsed” - they’re actually part of the context of the closest async method further up the call stack. For example:
陷阱在於 synchronous 方法不會通知 logical call context 任何內容不同。對於普通（非任務返回）同步方法，這很好;從邏輯調用上下文的角度來看，所有同步調用都是 「摺疊的」 - 它們實際上是調用堆疊中更上層最近的異步方法的上下文的一部分。例如：

In this example, Async does see the modification from its child Sync method. As I mentioned above, I prefer to think of this as the synchronous methods really being a part of the closest async context further up the stack. From the context’s perspective, Sync is just a part of Async.
在此示例中，Async 確實會從其子 Sync 方法中看到修改。正如我上面提到的，我更願意將此視為同步方法實際上是堆棧上最接近的異步上下文的一部分。從上下文的角度來看，Sync 只是 Async 的一部分。

When eliding async and await, you do need to be aware that the task-returning non-async method is seen by the context as though it were a regular synchronous method. So, if it does any modification of the logical call context, it will actually affect its parent context:
當省略 async 和 await 時，你確實需要注意，返回任務的非異步方法被上下文視為常規的同步方法。因此，如果它對logical call context 進行任何修改，它實際上會影響其父context：

This is a rare scenario, but it is one of the pitfalls of eliding async/await.
這是一種罕見的情況，但它是省略 async/await 的陷阱之一。

Recommended Guidelines  推薦準則

I suggest following these guidelines:
我建議遵循以下準則：

  1. Do not elide by default. Use the async and await for natural, easy-to-read code.
    默認情況下不省略。使用 async 和 await 獲得自然、易於閱讀的代碼。
  2. Do consider eliding when the method is just a passthrough or overload.
    當方法只是直通或重載時，請考慮省略。

You say "The expected asynchronous semantics are that exceptions are placed on the returned task." This surprised me - I would expect it to depend on the nature of the exception. In particular, if the exceptions relate to input validation (e.g., ArgumentNullException) then to me it feels odd to put that in the task. If the input is self-evidently bogus, you're never even going to start work, so although, as you say, "the returned task represents the execution of the method" I'd say that if you're throwing what Eric Lippert describes as a "boneheaded" exception, the work represented by the task never gets underway, so I don't really expect the method to return me a task.
Is your description of the "expected" semantics based on a design guide that I should be reading?

Stephen Cleary • https://stephencleary.com/
8 years ago (2016-12-02 07:11:15 pm)
In reply to Ian Griffiths

Yes, the original draft did have a section on boneheaded exceptions, but I cut it for length reasons.

Boneheaded precondition exceptions can either be placed on the returned task or thrown directly. There's plenty of code out there that follows either approach (or both!). And for boneheaded exceptions, it doesn't really matter. For all other exceptions, the only reasonable approach is to place them on the returned task.

Whether to eagerly throw precondition exceptions depends on your perspective, particularly this:

the work represented by the task never gets underway, so I don't really expect the method to return me a task.

The work is the method itself - that's what the task represents. So, if preconditions are run "before" the method (logically, not literally), then yes, it makes sense to want the exception thrown directly. But if preconditions are run at the beginning of the method, then it makes sense to fault the task. Jon Skeet is in the throw-directly camp, but I think it doesn't really matter - either way, precondition violations are boneheaded exceptions and thus shouldn't be caught anyway.

Ian Griffiths • http://www.interact-sw.co.uk/iangblog/
8 years ago (2016-12-16 11:11:01 pm)
In reply to Stephen Cleary

"The work is the method itself - that's what the task represents"

I think this is where we disagree. My view has always been that the task represents some work to be done.

Maybe it's my background in kernel mode device drivers (where everything is async) but the most straightforward view of any async operation to me is some work you've asked to be performed that will take a while to complete. When IO is involved, that very often means that the bulk of the work won't be done by the CPU - it'll be handled by some peripheral. At this point, saying that the task is the method seems way off base.

Stephen Cleary • https://stephencleary.com/
8 years ago (2016-12-17 10:10:58 pm)
In reply to Ian Griffiths

Yes, both views of Task are completely valid and useful.

On the one hand, Task certainly is a modern OVERLAPPED abstraction. It represents some work, often I/O-bound, which can be done by something off-CPU, and the Task will be notified when that work completes. That's a completely valid interpretation of Task, and one that is directly applicable when looking at tasks sourced from TaskFactory.FromAsync.

However, there's another interpretation of Task that is equally valid, particularly for tasks returned from methods. When you have an async method, the async state machine creates your Task and controls it for you. As long as the method awaits an (incomplete) awaitable, the task is not completed. When the method finishes, the task is completed. If the method returns a value, then that becomes the tasks's result. If the method throws an exception, then the task is faulted with that exception. In this way, a Task represents the execution of the method.

Both interpretations of Task are correct, and both valuable in different contexts. It is the latter version, however, that most end-users are more familiar with. The vast majority of async users have that view, and really have no idea how tasks "really work" at the lowest level - they only compose existing tasks into higher-level operations using async/await. All their experience with creating tasks is done via the async state machine. And the expectation from that mindset is that if an API method returns a task, then that task represents the execution of that method (and thus, they expect exceptions to be placed on the task).

Jean-Michel Deruty
8 years ago (2017-01-06 07:39:51 pm)
In reply to Ben Adams

It's not related to inlining at all. When eliding, you directly return the task to the caller, so the logic of the method returning the task is executed before (or in parallel to) the task itself. When you throw your exception, the stack doesn't contain the eliding method at all, as it doesn't await the task completion.

var task = GetWithKeywordsAsync();
var result = await task; // Exception thrown here

var task = GetElidingKeywordsAsync(); // Exception thrown here
var result = await task;

I think in the first snippet exception will be thrown on method call and in second on awaiting to task.

Stephen Cleary • https://stephencleary.com/
7 years ago (2017-12-11 08:30:02 am)
In reply to Hamlet Hakobyan

No; the comments are correct. The async keyword establishes the state machine, which catches the exception and places it on the returned task, so the exception is thrown when the task is await'ed. Without the async keyword, there's no state machine, so the exception is thrown immediately when the method is called.

Michael W.
4 years ago (2020-12-16 07:50:07 pm)

Hi, first thank you for your articles - I did read a lot of them and they are very useful!

When I tried to understand your samples regarding the exceptions I did think: that can not be true! So I created a small sample project. Assuming that 'DownloadStringAsync' will always throw an exception, the exception will occur in the calling code when awaiting the task - in all of your samples! So the first two samples with "await Get…Async()" throw an exception instead of "working fine". In the second two samples the exceptions occur during await too. Not when calling var task = GetElidingKeywordsAsync();

So I suppose I did a mistake defining the DownloadStringAsync method:

    private async Task<string> DownloadStringAsync(string url)
    {
        if (string.IsNullOrEmpty(url))
            throw new ArgumentException(nameof(url));

        await Task.Delay(100).ConfigureAwait(false);
        return url;
    }

The "url" is an empty string in all samples so DownloadStringAsync throws an ArgumentException.

Best regards, Michael

Stephen Cleary • https://stephencleary.com
4 years ago (2020-12-16 08:32:56 pm)
In reply to Michael W.

In this blog post, the exceptions I refer to as being thrown directly are exceptions thrown before the async method is called. Exceptions thrown from the async method itself work fine.
